{"id":909,"parent_id":0,"book_id":8,"content_id":1,"language_id":1,"display_order":909,"title":"Nineveh","subtitle":"","short_title":"Nineveh","uri":"/scriptures/bd/nineveh","content":[["div",{"id":"t1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/nineveh.t1","order":".000.2384"},[".title","Nineveh"],["div",{"id":"p1","uri":"/scriptures/bd/nineveh.p1","order":".000.2385"},"Capital of Assyria on the eastern bank of the Tigris, its traditional founder being Nimrod, the great hunter (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/gen/10.11-12"},"Gen. 10:11–12"],"). For several centuries Calah outstripped it in importance, but under Sennacherib it again became the capital (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/2-kgs/19.36"},"2 Kgs. 19:36"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/isa/37.37"},"Isa. 37:37"],"). It was for more than 200 years a great commercial center and also contained a large library of clay books. The city fell at the downfall of the Assyrian empire, 606",["span.small","B.C."],"See",["i",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/bd/assyria-and-babylonia"},"Assyria and Babylonia"],"."],"For prophecies concerning Nineveh, see",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/jonah/1.2"},"Jonah 1:2"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/jonah/3.2-7"},"3:2–7"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/jonah/4.11"},"4:11"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/nahum/1.1"},"Nahum 1:1"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/nahum/2.8"},"2:8"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/nahum/3.7"},"3:7"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/ot/zeph/2.13"},"Zeph. 2:13"],". Repentant Nineveh, a sign to the Jews (",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/matt/12.41"},"Matt. 12:41"],";",["a.scriptureRef",{"href":"/scriptures/nt/luke/11.32"},"Luke 11:32"],"). Its ruins have been carefully explored, and many important sculptures and inscriptions have been brought to light."]]],"refs":null}
